<subsection xml:id="subsubsec-combined-operations-involving-three-operations">
    <title>Combined operations involving three operations</title>
    <p>
      When you are required to perform combined operations involving three operations, carry out operations according to their order.
    </p>
    <p>
        Order of operations can be:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol marker= "i)">
            <li>
                <p>
                   Division <m>\rightarrow</m> Addition <m>\rightarrow</m> Subtraction
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Multiplication <m>\rightarrow</m> Addition <m>\rightarrow</m> Subtraction
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Division <m>\rightarrow</m> Multiplication <m>\rightarrow</m> Subtraction
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Division <m>\rightarrow</m> multiplication <m>\rightarrow</m> Subtraction
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                In Masomo college, <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> of the population study agriculture and <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> of the population study business.The rest of the population study artisan courses.
                 In <m>2024</m>, <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> of the agriculture students dropped out of the course to study mathematics, <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> of the business students went for attachment and <m>\frac{1}{5}</m> of the artisan students learned a new skill.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker= "a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker= "i)" >
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                      Working in groups of <m>5</m>, write an expression to calculate the fraction of the student population who pursued artisan courses? 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        What fraction of the student population pursued artisan courses? <m>\textbf{Hint:} {\color{blue}\text{Total population = 1}}</m> 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction of agriculture students dropped agriculture to do mathematics?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction of business students went for attachment?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction of the artisan students learned a new skill?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What fraction of the total population dropped agriculture, went for attachment, or learned a new skill? <m>\textbf{Hint:} {\color{blue}\text{ Add the fractions from questions b, c, and d}}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                         Calculate the fraction of the population that remained unchanged (did not drop agriculture, go for attachment, or learn a new skill)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss the order in which you have carried out the operations with other learners in class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Work out: <m>\frac{5}{6} \times \frac{3}{10}+ \frac{2}{3} \div \frac{4}{5}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To work out <m>\frac{5}{6} \times \frac{3}{10}+ \frac{2}{3} \div \frac{4}{5} </m>, follow the order:
            </p>
            <p>
                Division <m>\rightarrow</m> Multiplication <m>\rightarrow</m> Addition
            </p>
            <p>
                Carry out division by multiplying <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> by the reciprocal of <m>\frac{4}{5}</m>, which is <m>\frac{5}{4}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>=\amp \frac{5}{6} \times \frac{3}{10}+ \frac{2}{3} \times \frac{5}{4} </mrow>
                <mrow> \frac{\cancel{2}^1}{3} \times \frac{5}{\cancel{4}_2} =\amp \frac{1 \times 5}{3 \times 2}</mrow>
                <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{6} </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Carry out multiplication: <m>\frac{5}{6} \times \frac{3}{10} + \frac{5}{6}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{\cancel{5}^1}{\cancel{6}_2} \times \frac{\cancel{3}^1}{\cancel{10}_2} =\amp \frac{1 \times 1}{2 \times 2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{4} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Carry out addition: <m>\frac{1}{4} + \frac{5}{6}</m>. The LCM of <m>4</m> and <m>6</m> is <m>24</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{1}{4} + \frac{5}{6} =\amp \frac{6+20}{24} </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp \frac{26}{24}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplify <m>\frac{26}{24}</m> by dividing both the numerator and the denominator by <m>2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{26}{24} =\amp \frac{13}{12}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{13}{12}</m> written in an improper fraction is <m>1\frac{1}{12}</m>
            </p>
            

        </solution>
    </example>
